[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":628},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F":603,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F":612},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200524\u002F995184384\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":586,"date":587,"description":588,"extension":589,"lang":590,"meta":591,"navigation":82,"path":592,"readingMinutes":593,"seo":594,"standalone":595,"stem":596,"tags":597,"tldr":600,"updated":587,"url":601,"__hash__":602},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (8): How Memory Gets Allocated and Freed (Garbage Collection)","1000617685",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":579},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,30,33,36,39,43,46,113,124,130,133,136,142,146,149,306,309,413,420,426,429,519,528,532,545,551,555,575],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Let's talk about how JavaScript reclaims memory.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"garbage-collection","Garbage collection",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":23,"src":29},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-24%2011.07.15.png",[17,31,32],{},"Garbage collection is exactly what it sounds like — an automated memory-management mechanism. Every time a piece of code runs, it takes up some memory. Without garbage collection, that memory would fill up fast and you'd start running into lag and similar problems.",[17,34,35],{},"Here's a real-life way to think about it. Garbage collection is basically a contract. If you rent a car for two days, you have to return it (collect it) on the second day. Otherwise the rental company has no cars left to rent to anyone else.",[17,37,38],{},"Early programming languages didn't have garbage collection at all, so memory management was a big deal when you were building a system. If you flip through older tech books, a ton of them talk about managing memory by hand. So garbage collection takes a huge load off the developer — and it's a really important concept when you're writing JavaScript too.",[12,40,42],{"id":41},"how-javascript-reclaims-memory","How JavaScript reclaims memory",[17,44,45],{},"In an earlier chapter we learned that every function has its own chunk of memory:",[47,48,53],"pre",{"className":49,"code":50,"language":51,"meta":52,"style":52},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function a() { \u002F\u002F a's memory space\n\n}\nfunction b() { \u002F\u002F b's memory space\n\n}\n","js","",[54,55,56,77,84,90,103,108],"code",{"__ignoreMap":52},[57,58,61,65,69,73],"span",{"class":59,"line":60},"line",1,[57,62,64],{"class":63},"sWyjQ","function",[57,66,68],{"class":67},"sj_SG"," a",[57,70,72],{"class":71},"sMAXC","() { ",[57,74,76],{"class":75},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F a's memory space\n",[57,78,80],{"class":59,"line":79},2,[57,81,83],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":82},true,"\n",[57,85,87],{"class":59,"line":86},3,[57,88,89],{"class":71},"}\n",[57,91,93,95,98,100],{"class":59,"line":92},4,[57,94,64],{"class":63},[57,96,97],{"class":67}," b",[57,99,72],{"class":71},[57,101,102],{"class":75},"\u002F\u002F b's memory space\n",[57,104,106],{"class":59,"line":105},5,[57,107,83],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":82},[57,109,111],{"class":59,"line":110},6,[57,112,89],{"class":71},[17,114,115,116,119,120,123],{},"When we call ",[54,117,118],{},"a()"," or ",[54,121,122],{},"b()",", it takes up some memory. Once it finishes running, that memory gets released — just like functions getting popped off the execution stack we talked about before.",[17,125,126],{},[27,127],{"alt":128,"src":129},"Function release","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E9%87%8B%E6%94%BE%E5%9F%B7%E8%A1%8C%E5%A0%86%E7%96%8A.gif",[17,131,132],{},"But here's the key thing to watch out for. Garbage collection decides what to reclaim based on this rule: an object is only considered collectible \"when it's no longer being used, or no longer referenced by any other object.\"",[17,134,135],{},"Here's how MDN puts it:",[137,138,139],"blockquote",{},[17,140,141],{},"This algorithm reduces the definition of \"an object is no longer needed\" down to \"an object has no other object referencing it\". An object is considered garbage collectible if there are zero references pointing to it.",[12,143,145],{"id":144},"a-worked-example","A worked example",[17,147,148],{},"The course also gives a really nice example to verify this.",[47,150,152],{"className":49,"code":151,"language":51,"meta":52,"style":52},"function randomString(length) {\n  var result = '';\n  var characters = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789';\n  var charactersLength = characters.length;\n  for (var i = 0; i \u003C length; i++) {\n    result += characters.charAt(Math.floor(Math.random() * charactersLength));\n  }\n  return result;\n}\n",[54,153,154,171,189,203,220,253,286,292,301],{"__ignoreMap":52},[57,155,156,158,161,164,168],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,157,64],{"class":63},[57,159,160],{"class":67}," randomString",[57,162,163],{"class":71},"(",[57,165,167],{"class":166},"s_sBn","length",[57,169,170],{"class":71},") {\n",[57,172,173,176,179,182,186],{"class":59,"line":79},[57,174,175],{"class":63},"  var",[57,177,178],{"class":71}," result ",[57,180,181],{"class":63},"=",[57,183,185],{"class":184},"sTRMh"," ''",[57,187,188],{"class":71},";\n",[57,190,191,193,196,198,201],{"class":59,"line":86},[57,192,175],{"class":63},[57,194,195],{"class":71}," characters ",[57,197,181],{"class":63},[57,199,200],{"class":184}," 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789'",[57,202,188],{"class":71},[57,204,205,207,210,212,215,218],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,206,175],{"class":63},[57,208,209],{"class":71}," charactersLength ",[57,211,181],{"class":63},[57,213,214],{"class":71}," characters.",[57,216,167],{"class":217},"sCcAr",[57,219,188],{"class":71},[57,221,222,225,228,231,234,236,239,242,245,248,251],{"class":59,"line":105},[57,223,224],{"class":63},"  for",[57,226,227],{"class":71}," (",[57,229,230],{"class":63},"var",[57,232,233],{"class":71}," i ",[57,235,181],{"class":63},[57,237,238],{"class":217}," 0",[57,240,241],{"class":71},"; i ",[57,243,244],{"class":63},"\u003C",[57,246,247],{"class":71}," length; i",[57,249,250],{"class":63},"++",[57,252,170],{"class":71},[57,254,255,258,261,263,266,269,272,274,277,280,283],{"class":59,"line":110},[57,256,257],{"class":71},"    result ",[57,259,260],{"class":63},"+=",[57,262,214],{"class":71},[57,264,265],{"class":67},"charAt",[57,267,268],{"class":71},"(Math.",[57,270,271],{"class":67},"floor",[57,273,268],{"class":71},[57,275,276],{"class":67},"random",[57,278,279],{"class":71},"() ",[57,281,282],{"class":63},"*",[57,284,285],{"class":71}," charactersLength));\n",[57,287,289],{"class":59,"line":288},7,[57,290,291],{"class":71},"  }\n",[57,293,295,298],{"class":59,"line":294},8,[57,296,297],{"class":63},"  return",[57,299,300],{"class":71}," result;\n",[57,302,304],{"class":59,"line":303},9,[57,305,89],{"class":71},[17,307,308],{},"In short, the code above generates a really, really long random string to eat up some memory. And this next chunk will keep holding onto memory:",[47,310,312],{"className":49,"code":311,"language":51,"meta":52,"style":52},"var demoData = [];\nfunction getData() {\n  for (let i = 0; i \u003C 1000; i++) {\n    demoData.push(randomString(5000));\n  }\n}\ngetData();\nconsole.log(demoData);\n",[54,313,314,326,336,365,386,390,394,402],{"__ignoreMap":52},[57,315,316,318,321,323],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,317,230],{"class":63},[57,319,320],{"class":71}," demoData ",[57,322,181],{"class":63},[57,324,325],{"class":71}," [];\n",[57,327,328,330,333],{"class":59,"line":79},[57,329,64],{"class":63},[57,331,332],{"class":67}," getData",[57,334,335],{"class":71},"() {\n",[57,337,338,340,342,345,347,349,351,353,355,358,361,363],{"class":59,"line":86},[57,339,224],{"class":63},[57,341,227],{"class":71},[57,343,344],{"class":63},"let",[57,346,233],{"class":71},[57,348,181],{"class":63},[57,350,238],{"class":217},[57,352,241],{"class":71},[57,354,244],{"class":63},[57,356,357],{"class":217}," 1000",[57,359,360],{"class":71},"; i",[57,362,250],{"class":63},[57,364,170],{"class":71},[57,366,367,370,373,375,378,380,383],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,368,369],{"class":71},"    demoData.",[57,371,372],{"class":67},"push",[57,374,163],{"class":71},[57,376,377],{"class":67},"randomString",[57,379,163],{"class":71},[57,381,382],{"class":217},"5000",[57,384,385],{"class":71},"));\n",[57,387,388],{"class":59,"line":105},[57,389,291],{"class":71},[57,391,392],{"class":59,"line":110},[57,393,89],{"class":71},[57,395,396,399],{"class":59,"line":288},[57,397,398],{"class":67},"getData",[57,400,401],{"class":71},"();\n",[57,403,404,407,410],{"class":59,"line":294},[57,405,406],{"class":71},"console.",[57,408,409],{"class":67},"log",[57,411,412],{"class":71},"(demoData);\n",[17,414,415,416,419],{},"Basically, this stuffs a bunch of strings into the global variable ",[54,417,418],{},"demoData",", which keeps the memory occupied. Drop both of these snippets into Chrome and use the Memory tab to record memory usage, then watch how it changes.",[17,421,422],{},[27,423],{"alt":424,"src":425},"Memory usage","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-24%2016.07.04.png",[17,427,428],{},"In the image above you can see memory is sitting at 9.3 MB. Now refresh and swap in this version instead:",[47,430,432],{"className":49,"code":431,"language":51,"meta":52,"style":52},"function getData() {\n  var demoData = [];\n  for (var i = 0; i \u003C 1000; i++) {\n    demoData.push(randomString(5000))\n  }\n  console.log(demoData);\n}\ngetData()\n",[54,433,434,442,452,478,495,499,508,512],{"__ignoreMap":52},[57,435,436,438,440],{"class":59,"line":60},[57,437,64],{"class":63},[57,439,332],{"class":67},[57,441,335],{"class":71},[57,443,444,446,448,450],{"class":59,"line":79},[57,445,175],{"class":63},[57,447,320],{"class":71},[57,449,181],{"class":63},[57,451,325],{"class":71},[57,453,454,456,458,460,462,464,466,468,470,472,474,476],{"class":59,"line":86},[57,455,224],{"class":63},[57,457,227],{"class":71},[57,459,230],{"class":63},[57,461,233],{"class":71},[57,463,181],{"class":63},[57,465,238],{"class":217},[57,467,241],{"class":71},[57,469,244],{"class":63},[57,471,357],{"class":217},[57,473,360],{"class":71},[57,475,250],{"class":63},[57,477,170],{"class":71},[57,479,480,482,484,486,488,490,492],{"class":59,"line":92},[57,481,369],{"class":71},[57,483,372],{"class":67},[57,485,163],{"class":71},[57,487,377],{"class":67},[57,489,163],{"class":71},[57,491,382],{"class":217},[57,493,494],{"class":71},"))\n",[57,496,497],{"class":59,"line":105},[57,498,291],{"class":71},[57,500,501,504,506],{"class":59,"line":110},[57,502,503],{"class":71},"  console.",[57,505,409],{"class":67},[57,507,412],{"class":71},[57,509,510],{"class":59,"line":288},[57,511,89],{"class":71},[57,513,514,516],{"class":59,"line":294},[57,515,398],{"class":67},[57,517,518],{"class":71},"()\n",[17,520,521,522,524,525,527],{},"This time ",[54,523,418],{}," is created inside ",[54,526,398],{},", so when the function finishes running, that memory gets released — that's garbage collection. But you'll notice memory is still sitting at 9.3 MB.",[17,529,530],{},[27,531],{"alt":424,"src":425},[17,533,534,535,537,538,540,541,544],{},"At this point you might be thinking, \"Wait, isn't ",[54,536,418],{}," created inside ",[54,539,398],{},"? Shouldn't that memory get freed?\" You're right — it should. The reason memory is still held is that ",[54,542,543],{},"console"," also takes up memory. So all you need to do is clear the console (don't reset it), and you'll see memory drop to 4.3 MB.",[17,546,547],{},[27,548],{"alt":549,"src":550},"Console usage","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-24%2016.14.14.png",[12,552,554],{"id":553},"references","References",[556,557,558,568],"ul",{},[559,560,561],"li",{},[562,563,567],"a",{"href":564,"rel":565},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[566],"nofollow","Hexschool - JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[559,569,570],{},[562,571,574],{"href":572,"rel":573},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FMemory_Management",[566],"Memory Management",[576,577,578],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":52,"searchDepth":79,"depth":79,"links":580},[581,582,583,584,585],{"id":14,"depth":79,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":79,"text":23},{"id":41,"depth":79,"text":42},{"id":144,"depth":79,"text":145},{"id":553,"depth":79,"text":554},"JavaScript","2020-05-24 10:56:06","Let's talk about how JavaScript reclaims memory. This post covers what garbage collection actually is, why older languages made you manage memory by hand, the rule JavaScript uses to decide when an object is safe to collect, and a hands-on Chrome experiment to watch memory get allocated and freed in real time.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection","3",{"title":6,"description":588},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection",[586,598,599],"JavaScript Core","Execution Context & Scope",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F24\u002Fjs-core-08-memory-allocation-garbage-collection\u002F","2EWVC7AZgdNVNz8mkN4QE1_Jzpk2-qPFPYu5k3XfNn0",{"newer":604,"older":608},{"url":605,"title":606,"date":607},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fpixijs-v5-16-game-hp-bar\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (16) - Building a Game HP Bar","2020-05-25 09:00:08",{"url":609,"title":610,"date":611},"\u002Fen\u002Fcss\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F23\u002Fcss-design-patterns-sass-7-1-pattern\u002F","CSS Design Patterns — Sass 7-1 Pattern","2020-05-23 21:00:52",[613,618,623],{"url":614,"title":615,"date":616,"readingMinutes":617},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":619,"title":620,"date":621,"readingMinutes":622},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":624,"title":625,"date":626,"readingMinutes":627},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013060859]